{{Infobox person | name = Arabella Chapman | image = Arabella_Chapman._Tintype.jpg | alt = | caption = Arabella Chapman Miller | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name --> | birth_date = 1859 | birth_place = Jersey City, N.J. | death_date = {{Death year and age|1927|1859}} | death_place = Albany, N.Y. | nationality = | other_names = Arabella Chapman Miller | occupation = | known_for = }} '''Arabella Chapman''' (1859–1927) was an [[African-American]] woman who is best remembered for being the first student to graduate from upstate [[New York (state)|New York]]'s Albany School for Educating People of Color, later known as [[Albany High School (New York)|Albany High School]].<ref name="Hughes">{{cite book|last1=Hughes|first1=Marian I.|title=Refusing Ignorance; The Struggle to Educate Black Children in [[Albany, New York|Albany]], New York 1816-1873|date=1998|publisher=Mount Ida Press|location=Albany, N.Y.|isbn=978-0-9625368-2-3}}</ref>
==Biography== She was born free in [[Jersey City, New Jersey]]. By 1870, her family had migrated to Albany, New York, where Chapman would be raised in that city's thriving African-American community. She first attended Wilberforce School, before going on to Albany Free Academy (now Albany High School).<ref>[https://arabellachapman.history.lsa.umich.edu/?page_id=1001 "Arabella Chapman (1859-1927)"], The Arabella Chapman Project.</ref> In 1877, she became the first African American to graduate from the Free Academy, and by 1880, she was teaching music. Her marriage to Clarence Miller led Chapman to leave Albany, traveling with Miller to [[North Adams, Massachusetts]], where he would be employed as a waiter and she would raise their children.<ref name="Hughes"/>
Chapman created two photographic albums in the 1870s and 1880s. These albums survive in the collection of the [[University of Michigan]]'s [[William L. Clements Library]]. They are rare items that document Chapman's personal and political vision. The photographic portraits included those of notable figures such as [[Abraham Lincoln]], [[Frederick Douglass]], and [[John Brown (abolitionist)|John Brown]]. Most striking are the portraits of Chapman herself, along with her family and friends. Through Chapman's careful curatorship, the albums convey a sense of how African Americans constructed their social and cultural worlds in the [[Reconstruction Era|post-Civil War era]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Arabella Chapman carte-de-visite albums 1878-[1890s]|url=http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/f/findaid/idx/c/clementsgrfx/umich-wcl-F-82cha?cginame=findaid-idx;id=navbarbrowselink;subview=standard;view=reslist|website=William L. Clements Library|publisher=William L. Clements Library|accessdate=August 12, 2014}}</ref>
Chapman's photo albums were exhibited in the 2013–14 exhibition, Proclaiming Emancipation, at the University of Michigan as examples of how the memory of the [[American Civil War|Civil War]], Emancipation, and citizenship was constructed by ordinary people.<ref>{{cite web|title=Proclaiming Emancipation|url=http://clements.umich.edu/exhibits/online/proclaiming_emancipation/emancipation-abolition.php|website=William L. Clements Library. Exhibitions.|publisher=William L. Clements Library|accessdate=August 12, 2014}}</ref>
Arabella Chapman's photo albums have been curated as part of an on-line exhibit, The Arabella Chapman Project at arabellachapman.com.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Arabella Chapman Project|url=http://www.arabellachapman.com|website=The Arabella Chapman Project|publisher=The Regents of the University of Michigan and the William L. Clements Library|accessdate=May 31, 2015}}</ref>
