{{other uses|Atto (disambiguation)}} {{Infobox Christian leader | type = | honorific-prefix = [[Canonization|Saint]] Bishop | name = Atto | honorific-suffix = [[Vallumbrosan Order|O.S.B. Vall.]] | title = [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Pistoia|Bishop of Pistoia]] | image = Bernardino Poccetti e aiuti, affreschi della sagrestia di san bartolomeo di ripoli, 1585, fregio 08 beato atto vescovo (cropped).JPG | image_size = | alt = | caption = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | church = [[Roman Catholic Church]] | archdiocese = | province = | metropolis = | diocese = Pistoia | see = Pistoia | elected = | appointed = 1133 | enthroned = | term = | term_start = | term_end = 22 May 1153 | quashed = | predecessor = Ildebrando Guidi | successor = Tracio | opposed = | other_post = <!---------- Orders ----------> | ordination = | ordained_by = | consecration = c. 1133 | consecrated_by = | cardinal = | created_cardinal_by = | rank = Bishop <!---------- Personal details ----------> | birth_name = Atto | birth_date = c. 1070 | birth_place = [[Beja (Portugal)|Beja]], [[Portugal]] | death_date = 22 May 1153 (aged 83) | death_place = [[Pistoia]], [[Italy]] | buried = | tomb = | resting_place_coordinates = | nationality = | religion = | residence = | parents = | spouse = | children = | occupation = | profession = | previous_post = | education = | alma_mater = | motto = | signature = | signature_alt = | coat_of_arms = | coat_of_arms_alt = <!---------- Sainthood ----------> | feast_day = {{unbulleted list|22 May|21 June (Pistoia)}} | venerated = Roman Catholic Church | saint_title = | beatified_date = | beatified_place = | beatified_by = | canonized_date = 24 January 1605 | canonized_place = [[Saint Peter's Basilica]], [[Papal States]] | canonized_by = [[Pope Clement VIII]] | attributes = {{unbulleted list|Episcopal attire|Pastoral staff|Benedictine habit}} | patronage = | shrine = | suppressed_date = <!---------- Other ----------> | module = | other = }}
[[Canonization|Saint]] '''Atto''' (1070 – 22 May 1153) was a [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]] [[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] bishop and a professed member from the [[Vallumbrosan Order]] as well as the [[Bishop of Pistoia]] and a noted historiographer.
He was born at [[Beja (Portugal)|Beja]] in the Portuguese region of [[Alentejo]] in 1070. He became Abbot of [[Vallombrosa]] (in [[Tuscany]]) in 1105, and in 1135 was made [[Bishop of Pistoia]], also in Tuscany. He wrote lives of [[St. John Gualbert]] and [[St. Bernard of Vallombrosa]], [[bishop of Parma]]. In 1145 he transferred to [[Pistoia]] certain relics of the Apostle [[St. James of Compostella]]. His correspondence on that occasion is found in [[Ferdinando Ughelli]], ''Italia sacra'', VII, 296.
