{{Infobox person |name = Sima Ćirković |image = Sima Ćirković, SANU.jpg |image_size = 200px |birth_date = {{birth date|1929|1|29}} |birth_place = [[Osijek]], [[Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes]] |death_date = {{Death date and age|2009|11|14|1929|1|29}} |death_place = [[Belgrade]], [[Serbia]] |alma_mater = |occupation = Historian }}
'''Simeon "Sima" Ćirković''' (January 29, 1929 – November 14, 2009) was a Serbian historian and member of the [[Serbian Academy of Science and Arts]]. He was also a member of the [[Academy of Sciences and Arts of Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[Montenegrin Academy of Sciences and Arts]], [[Yugoslav Academy of Sciences and Arts]] and the [[Vojvodina Academy of Sciences and Arts]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=E|first=B|title=Sima Ćirković, istoričar (Sima Ćirković, historian)|journal=Blic|date=November 17, 2009|url=http://www.blic.rs/Kultura/120874/Sima-Cirkovic-istoricar-|accessdate=19 May 2011|language=Serbian|quote= koji je bio i član ANU BiH, JAZU, CANU, VANU i Evropske akademije za istoriju Brisel.}}</ref> His works focused on medieval Serbian history.
== Activism == In 1986 Ćirković exercised a criticism of the [[Memorandum of the Serbian Academy of Sciences and Arts]] while during the [[Siege of Dubrovnik]] he and other Yugoslav historians sent an open letter to the Yugoslavian forces asking them to not damage historical district of the city.<ref name="Popov2000">{{cite book|last=Popov|first=Nebojša|title=The road to war in Serbia: trauma and catharsis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GkBmdCwHuDsC|accessdate=19 May 2011|year=2000|publisher=Central European University Press|isbn=978-963-9116-56-6}}</ref>
